Ashton Sanders's outfit actually hit the Gilded Age theme pretty accurately.  See, we don't call the Gilded Age "golden" for a reason. It's gold /covered/, not made of gold. It seems shiny and glamorous on the outside, but below the surface, it is anything but. The Gilded Age was the era where monopolies like Standard Oil flourished at the expense of the working class, and was rife with the bloodshed of the Civil War.   I bring this up because Sanders deliberately wore that suit as an homage to the Buffalo Soldiers, an all-Black cavalry that was established in 1866 (well within the bounds of the time period) to fight in the Civil War. As a black man, he would not have gotten to enjoy the luxurious lifestyle of the Astors or the Vanderbilts. Instead, he would likely be on the battlefield fighting for his right to exist or suffering under the extreme conditions of the workforce.  The suit itself is not made to be an exact replica, but to capture the essence of the uniforms worn by the Buffalo Soldiers. It still, however, carries a similar silhouette and incorporates the motif of the blue and gold heralding in a way that is reminiscent, but not 100% historically accurate to the actual clothing the regiments donned as they rode or marched into battle.

Not quite. But close. They were established in 1866. The Civil War ended in April of 1865. They were established for the sole purpose of suppressing, and if necessary, obliterating the American Plains Indians (Apaches, Comanches, Blackfoot, Sioux etc- basically the most advanced fighting tribes) in the US government's disturbing pursuit of "Manifest Destiny". The Buffalo Soldiers indeed gave the American Plains Indians hell, and were a crucial factor in their eventual near total annihilation and brutal defeat. The black regiments that fought in the civil war were absolutely NOT the Buffalo Soldiers, though maybe a couple black civil war soldiers that lived and weren't maimed AND decided to continue their occupation in the US military (a rare case indeed) perhaps joined this regiment. Why not. They were paid more doing this than at other jobs and given more respect. The Indians are the ones that actually gave them the nickname "Buffalo Soldiers". You can easily remember this by their name and where the buffalo were located. In the west. Whereas the Civil War was fought in the southeastern United States where there were no buffalo. Lol. Here:  "American Plains Indians who fought against these soldiers referred to the black cavalry troops as "buffalo soldiers" because of their dark, curly hair, which resembled a buffalo's coat and because of their fierce nature of fighting. The nickname soon became synonymous with all African-American regiments formed in 1866." -Npc dot gov  Also, the Buffalo Soldiers are considered to be America's first Park Rangers. ğŸ–¤  Edit: typo

Even the fabric choice was deliberate and on theme - denim became popular in the 1870's, partially due to how cheap it was. And it was cheap because black sharecroppers weren't being paid fair wages for their cotton. Denim was also commonly worn in the 1870s by working folks and soldiers due to its relative durability.

For the gilded age architecture (Blake's dress) this is a direct correlation to the Statue of liberty that was made out of copper and then when oxidized turned a teal shade (as copper does).  The lines and cuts in the dress are very accurate to the gilded age accents in the major building in NY at the time that had those kinds of accents.  Copper was used in piping and sewage back then an it was much cheaper and safer than steel, so the copper makes sense.  However, as time when along copper became less popular and more expensive as it heats even more rapidly than steel or stainless steel.    Blake did a fantastic job thinking outside the box, and frankly this years theme sucked as many of the years themes have sucked and I'm tired of the "hollywood glam, remember history" trope.  Everyone from that era is dead and I wish we would leave them and their clothes in the damn grave.  Thank you for attending my Ted Talk.

Okay, when hearing this theme, I had an immediate idea for what I thought would be a fun outfit/event (because everyone is loving these carpet gimmicks or outfit transformations). I thought wearing a traditional mourning dress of the era--heavy, dense, deep black, fully period accurate. Hoever, in line with how a woman is supposed to 'come out of mourning' slowly color is revealed or added in the dress. Traditionally colors are supposed to be re-added to the wardrobe in a specific order. Usually starting with subtle navy colors then slowly becoming lighter in color, then finally patterns can be reintroduced. Imagine revealing a navy stripe or strip of fabric, then as you proceed down the carpet you nonchalantly reveal more and more bright colors until finally at the end of the carpet it transforms into a bright ensemble! Just wanna put it out there that I think Ashton Sanders' look deserves some review and more appreciation: the style of the suit feels reminiscent of a bellhop uniform, possibly a reference to POC being in positions of service especially during the Guilded Age, in a similar way that Riz Ahmed dedicated his outfit to immigrant workers during the Gilded Age. Furthermore, denim was invented around the 1870s, and his contacts and fake fangs are a reference to the creation of vampiric tropes in the late 19th century. Of course there's also the details pointed out in video of the corseted look added to the uniform, as well as the gaudy, golden detailing on the outfit, as well as epaulettes that add to the references. Imo this was actually a thought through outfit with an interesting sprinkling of references

The term "gilded age" comes from Mark Twain to describe the reality of the mass socioeconomic conditions of that time in the US and western Europe. Behind the glamorous, opulent exterior coating of gold, wealth, and "beauty", there is a rough, bleak, dark, and not pretty at all reality for the vast majority. For most, the gilded age was a time of immense suffering, destitution, and abject poverty, the 15 hour work days, terrible polluted and sickly cities and towns, child labor, and the relentless, ruthless exploitation of people and the environment, all for the benefit of a few who were part of a privileged bourgeois class, those who got to dress in obscene fashion like this.  Kind of funny how these rich privileged people only know the era as a time of opulent consumption and not as an era that led to a powerful emergence of the working class via labor unions and other organizing, to take power for these exploiters and back to themselves, so they try to emulate those privileged exploiters and so many clap like seals at the theatre and show, all while most of the country (and the world) is living paycheck to paycheck in economic insecurity or downright abject poverty, the irony eludes them and so many of the celebrity idolators.

Creativity emerges from limitations (in this case: the theme). Because it challenges the designer to work around it making innovative and artistic design solutions while respecting the given context. Most of the designers and/or fashion houses in the event definitely forgot or disregarded how to "design" accordingly. Just as some here mentioned, some outfits are just straight-out advertisement for the brands. It's truly another missed opportunity that other brands and designers alike would prove that they are at least still worthy of their success status/ creative recognition they receive. Most want to stand-out but not in a good way. And it's become a lame overused excuse to wear uncreative, incompetent (theme-deviant) outfits. The theme is relatively facile. It's either be inspired by victorian/ gilded age fashion/silhouettes, incorporate gold (gilded) detailing, or derive from other artistic expressions that signifies the prosperity of the era. I know most of the time it's not the celebrities' fault as they are only sponsored. It could've been understandable to some extent. But considering the amount of attendees who did not conform to the theme is quite disappointing.

As a history buff, the 1870s-1900s is SUCH a rich time period full of insane fashions and incredibly important political and cultural events. There was so much that could've been done with the theme, from fashion references to historical event references. But I feel that everyone just collectively used this as an excuse to play historical dress-up from any time period they wanted. A complete disregard for the nuance of that period by lumping it with the mindset of "All Of History was the Exact Same"

But I think it was on theme actually, Thom Browne I believe said it was a white tie inspired by the gilded era and Kourtney's is a deconstructed version of Travis' look since this is the first time he's dressed a couple together he wanted to make it cohesive.  When I saw it I thought Kourtney's looks specifically could be a reference to the textile mills and tailoring industry that bloomed in the gilded age along side other unskilled labor forms ( mining, railroad workers etc) did with all the immigrants coming to east coast to work, especially New York. Fun to see them with a New York designer as well for this theme. I don't LOVE the look but it's def not getting the credit it deserves! :)
Â @Khs1606Â  I didn't see that quote but it makes sense. I wish that the designers gave out crib notes on the idea behind the outfit so the wearer could explain!

Â @_crusoeÂ  The quote was on someones instastory, but I found it! It's from the behind the scenes article Kourtney's platform posted.  â€œThom presented us with his vision, which was Travis being perfectly polished in a gilded era-inspired white-tie formal look and me being an extension of him, like melting off him almostâ€”the unrefined, undone version, using all of the pieces from his look to create this raw take on a Gilded Age gown using menâ€™s apparel (with the muslin cummerbund corset and the bustle made of his jacket). We were the first couple he had ever dressed together, and he said that it was very important to him that we tell a story as a couple and go beyond just a surface-level Gilded Age tux and ball gown.â€

Yes, I saw so many people thinking that attendees were supposed to be dressed in 18th century french clothes or English Regency wear... and I was like wait! No! I think they were going for art nouveau which is a style that came before Art Deco circa 1890.

Although New Yorkâ€™s most prominent Art Nouveau buildings were sharper in shape they definitely shined for their natural forms and shapes, specially those curved and smoothed. You can see this very clearly in the CUNY Graduate Center. I am pretty sure that the references are the sharp shapes of the Chrysler building, the General Electric Building, etc. All built in the 30s. Art Deco was named after the Exposition of International Des Arts Decoratifs of 1925 therefore it lies far from the Guilded Age, although of course all genres canâ€™t be circunscribes to a strict era because they are in certain ways a condensation of previous experiments.

I think they messed them up, which is pretty common because everything that goes from the 1880s to the 1940s is pretty blurred for many people. The Gilded Age is quite strictly understood as the period between two big national crises (the Panics of 1873 and 1893) which, as usual, opened the door for a bigger concentration of wealth for the most aristocratic bourgeoisie in the US and certain new wealths that niched from the collapse. It mustnâ€™t be confused with the Belle Ã‰poque which starts with the foundation of the Third French Republic until 1914. The period between the second half of the 1890s to 1916 is identified in the US as the Progressive Era with the growth of social activism, suffragism, Taylorism and the Socialist Party of America. It does have its own art forms and investigations but so many studies concentrate in the politics and economics as something separated from art that it is rather overlooked or misrepresented. In fashion that was a sort of transition from bustles to flappers and in architecture more institutional classicist and Romanesque buildings were combined with the American Craftsman movement, inspired by arts and crafts and the Art Nouveau.

I think Ashton Sanders is on theme, actually. He's wearing all denim, with metallic gold trim along the seams.   Working class Americans started wearing jeans in the 1850's, but rivets were only added to jeans in the early 1870's which is the beginning of the gilded age. It's called "gilded" instead of "golden" because a few people were extremely rich, while everyone who worked for them lived in poverty. He's referencing the working class clothing of the era instead of high fashion, and that makes perfect sense for this theme.  Oh and the epaulets and stripes on a dark blue fabric also reference the Union army uniform. The civil war ended in 1865 but the outcome of the war would have defined everyday life for most people in the decade after.

IN DEFENSE OF CARDI: She is giving me Portrait of Madame X/John Singer Sargent silhouette and styling, She is literally GILDED in that she is dripping in gold but again the silhouette and neck line is highly referential to the gown in the 1883/1884 Madame X painting. Sargent was an icon in portraying sensual, feminine beauty during this period, consider the history of the painting, courtesy of the Met itself:  "Working without a commission but with his sitterâ€™s complicity, he emphasized her daring personal style, showing the right strap of her gown slipping from her shoulder. At the Salon of 1884, the portrait received more ridicule than praise. Sargent repainted the shoulder strap and kept the work for over thirty years." Could you think of a more Gilded Age story to translate for Cardi B?  In the painting, the shoulder straps themselves, symbols of Madame X's daring sensual style AND her censure, are gold chains attached to the neckline with circular gold embellishments which already resembled the Versace coin motif.  I think the translation of the Versace coins  to a completely gilded version of the dress is genius, it's a rejection of Cardi and Madame X's censorship, and a celebration of Cardi's unabashedly sensual and bold style in the modern era.
